label.value: decreased lipid binding

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which occurrence of lipid binding by a gene product (usually a protein) in a mutant is decreased. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.

definition.value: This term can mean that the mutated gene product itself binds heme less than wild type, or that a mutation in one gene decreases heme binding by a second gene product. When using this term, it is therefore recommended to note the specific protein(s) affected.

label.value: decreased membrane lipid binding

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which occurrence of binding to a lipid in a membrane by a gene product (usually a protein) in a mutant is decreased. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.

label.value: abolished membrane lipid binding

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which binding to a lipid in a membrane by a gene product does not occur. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.

label.value: normal replication fork processing

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which replication fork processing is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). Replication fork processing is process in which a DNA replication fork that has stalled (due to DNA damage, DNA secondary structure, bound proteins, dNTP shortage, or other causes) is repaired and replication is restarted.

label.value: decreased replication fork processing

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the occurrence of replication fork processing is decreased. Replication fork processing is process in which a DNA replication fork that has stalled (due to DNA damage, DNA secondary structure, bound proteins, dNTP shortage, or other causes) is repaired and replication is restarted.

label.value: premature protein localization to meiotic spindle pole body during prophase I

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the meiotic spindle pole body is begins earlier than normal during prophase of the first meiotic nuclear division.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term. Use this term for cells in which in which the re-accumulation of some spindle pole body components does not occur at the onset of meiosis I.

label.value: delayed onset of protein localization to meiotic spindle pole body during meiosis I

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the meiotic spindle pole body begins later than normal during the first meiotic nuclear division.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term. Use this term for cells in which in which the re-accumulation of some spindle pole body components does not occur at the onset of meiosis I.

label.value: abnormal meiotic spindle pole body duplication

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which meiotic spindle pole body duplication is abnormal.

label.value: increased meiotic spindle pole body duplication

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the occurrence of meiotic spindle pole body duplication is increased.

label.value: abnormal cellular process during meiotic cell cycle

value.value: A phenotype in which a specific cellular process is abnormal in the meiotic cell cycle.

definition.value: This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.

label.value: decreased telomere tethering at nuclear periphery during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which telomere tethering at the nuclear periphery is decreased.

label.value: abnormal eisosome

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount, distribution, morphology, or other physical characteristic of the eisosome is abnormal. The eisosome consists of a furrow-like plasma membrane sub-domain and associated integral transmembrane proteins, and the proteins (eisosome filaments) that form a scaffolding lattice on the cytoplasmic face.

label.value: eisosomes present in decreased numbers

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells contain fewer eisosomes than normal.

label.value: long eisosome filament

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the eisosome filament is longer than normal.

label.value: long eisosome filaments present in decreased numbers

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells contain fewer, and longer, eisosome filaments than normal.

label.value: decreased colocalization of cortical endoplasmic reticulum with eisosomes

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the endoplasmic reticulum (ER) colocalizes with eisosomes to a lower extent than normal.

label.value: increased colocalization of cortical endoplasmic reticulum with eisosomes

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the endoplasmic reticulum (ER) colocalizes with eisosomes to a greater extent than normal.

label.value: decreased cortical endoplasmic reticulum remodeling

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cortical endoplasmic reticulum (ER) remodeling occurs to a lower extent than normal. Cortical ER remodeling is the dynamic spatial rearrangement of ER tubules near the cell cortex.

label.value: normal interphase mitotic telomere clustering during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which telomere clustering is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). Telomere clustering gathers telomeres during or prior to tethering to the nuclear periphery during interphase of the mitotic cell cycle.

label.value: decreased Tf body tethering to centromere

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which nuclear chromatin organization is abnormal, such regions containing transposons (Tf2 elements) are tethered to the centromere to a lower extent than normal.

label.value: increased Tf body tethering to centromere

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which nuclear chromatin organization is abnormal, such regions containing transposons (Tf2 elements) are tethered to the centromere to a greater extent than normal.

label.value: decreased protein localization to nucleoplasm during cellular response to DNA damage

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the nucleoplasm is decreased during a cellular response to a DNA damage stimulus.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased cortical endoplasmic reticulum remodeling

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cortical endoplasmic reticulum (ER) remodeling occurs to a greater extent than normal. Cortical ER remodeling is the dynamic spatial rearrangement of ER tubules near the cell cortex.

label.value: abnormal mitochondrion inheritance

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which mitochondrion inheritance is abnormal. Mitochondrion inheritance is a cellular process that results in the distribution of mitochondria into daughter cells after mitosis or meiosis, mediated by interactions between mitochondria and the cytoskeleton.

label.value: abnormal mitochondrion inheritance during meiotic cell cycle

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which mitochondrion inheritance is abnormal during the meiotic cell cycle. Mitochondrion inheritance is a cellular process that results in the distribution of mitochondria into daughter cells after mitosis or meiosis, mediated by interactions between mitochondria and the cytoskeleton.

label.value: normal mitochondrion inheritance during meiotic cell cycle

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which mitochondrion inheritance is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) during the meiotic cell cycle. Mitochondrion inheritance is a cellular process that results in the distribution of mitochondria into daughter cells after mitosis or meiosis, mediated by interactions between mitochondria and the cytoskeleton.

label.value: normal cellular process during meiotic cell cycle

value.value: A phenotype in which a specific cellular process is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) in the meiotic cell cycle.

definition.value: This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.

label.value: normal protein localization to euchromatin

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to euchromatin is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased protein localization to euchromatin

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to euchromatin is increased.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: decreased protein localization to nuclear exosome focus

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to nuclear exosome foci is decreased. Nuclear exosome foci, also called Mmi1 foci, are small structures that form within the nucleus, and contain proteins involved in degrading meiosis-specific RNAs during the mitotic cell cycle, such as Mmi1, Iss10, and Red1.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal level of meiotic gene mRNA during vegetative growth

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of one or more RNAs that are normally expressed during meiosis measured in a cell is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: viable branched, swollen vegetative cell

value.value: A cell morphology phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a cell is viable and branched, and has a larger volume than normal. In a swollen cell, both length and diameter may be greater than normal, although the cell is only considered elongated if the length:diameter ratio is also greater than normal.

label.value: normal protein localization to lateral cell cortex during vegetative growth

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the lateral cell cortex is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal protein localization to non-growing cell tip

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the non-growing cell tip is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abnormal dynamic protein localization to cell tip

value.value: A cell phenotype in which a protein that is normally dynamically localized to one or both cell tips shows an abnormal temporal pattern of localization. For example, a protein may move from one cell tip to the other at an altered frequency or amplitude.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal protein localization to late endosome membrane

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the late endosome membrane is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: decreased protein galactosylation during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the galactosylation of one or more specific proteins, or of specific protein sites, occurs to a lower extent than normal. Protein galactosylation is the addition of a galactose residue to a protein amino acid.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal protein galactosylation during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which protein galactosylation is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). Protein galactosylation is the addition of a galactose residue to a protein amino acid.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abnormal UDP-glucose 4-epimerase activity

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of UDP-glucose 4-epimerase activity is abnormal.

label.value: decreased UDP-glucose 4-epimerase activity

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of UDP-glucose 4-epimerase activity is decreased.

label.value: decreased cellular UDP-galactose level

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of UDP-galactose measured in the cell is lower than normal.

label.value: increased cytosolic UDP-galactose level

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of UDP-galactose measured in the cytosol is higher than normal.

label.value: lysed spherical vegetative cell

value.value: A cell phenotype in which a spherical vegetative cell lyses, i.e. the plasma membrane ruptures and cytoplasm is lost.

label.value: pear-shaped vegetative cell with actin localized to rounded end

value.value: A cell phenotype in which a vegetative cell is pear-shaped, and in which actin is localized only to the rounded end of the cell.

label.value: increased protein localization to CENP-A containing chromatin

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to CENP-A containing chromatin is increased.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abolished UDP-galactose biosynthetic process

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the biosynthesis of UDP-galactose does not occur.

label.value: increased transcription from SRE promoter

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which transcription from a promoter that contains one or more SRE elements occurs to a greater extent than normal.

label.value: abnormal protein aggregate center formation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which protein aggregate center formation is abnormal. Protein aggregate centers are composed of chaperones and misfolded proteins, and are reversibly formed in the nucleus and cytosol to shield thermosensitive proteins from degradation until conditions allow disaggregation and refolding.

label.value: decreased protein aggregate center formation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which protein aggregate center formation is decreased. Protein aggregate centers are composed of chaperones and misfolded proteins, and are reversibly formed in the nucleus and cytosol to shield thermosensitive proteins from degradation until conditions allow disaggregation and refolding.

label.value: abolished protein aggregate center formation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which protein aggregate center formation does not occur. Protein aggregate centers are composed of chaperones and misfolded proteins, and are reversibly formed in the nucleus and cytosol to shield thermosensitive proteins from degradation until conditions allow disaggregation and refolding.
